english:
  title: A Song of the Nakdong River
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Yellow Pool's source scarcely filled a cup,
    yet here it rushes, grown boundless and wide.
    One river splits six dozen states in two,
    and ferries multiply at countless fords.
    Straight down to the sea four hundred leagues it flows,
    fair winds bearing merchants back and forth.

    We set out at dawn from Moonwave Pavilion,
    rest at evening in the Waterwatch Tower.
    Below it, thousand-ton barges crowd the dock,
    while southern folk endure their tax collector's squeeze.
    The rice jars empty, acorns and chestnuts gone,
    yet by the river's edge, songs and feasts, fat cattle slaughtered.

    The emperor's messengers flash like shooting stars,
    but none inquire the names of skulls beside the road.
    Wild winds keen like maidens, grass bows for princes,
    haze shimmers thin above the spring waters.
    My gaze reaches far to where the birds take flight,
    yet home's flowers bloom renewed in absent springs.
    In lean years, no one lingers for such pleasures.

    Leaning on a pillar, I sing aloud,
    when suddenly spring's joy grows sharp and small.
    The white gull seems to mock me—
    now hurried, now at ease, now hurried again.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Yellow Pool' (黃池) refers to the Nakdong River's source in the mountains of central Korea, a traditional poetic opening suggesting humble origins that grow into something magnificent.
    - The river's division of 'six dozen states' reflects the administrative divisions through which it flows, emphasizing its economic and political significance.
    - This poem contrasts the grandeur of imperial commerce and power with the suffering of common people—an implicit social critique characteristic of 15th-century Korean literati.
